Thus, there is a strong argument that giant iceberg formation has a net positive climate
beneﬁt by growing important negative feedbacks [14,18]. Of course cost–beneﬁt analysis of giant
icebergs concerns much more than blue carbon, and recovery to previous climax biodiversity
may take many decades to hundreds of years [7,10]. Weighing up potential blue carbon gains
versus buttressing of ice sheet losses, sea level, gas exchange and heat absorption changes would
be a complex calculation, involving some stochastic and chaotic elements. Such a calculation,
if meaningfully possible, might not support the positive viewpoint of ice shelf disintegration,
especially if there was a very high-proﬁle and expensive research station on one of them.
